n, John Patrick, Kieran, Colm, Donal, Brennan, Caitlin.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Briain</b> ‘descendant of <i>Brian</i>’, a personal name probably based on the element <i>bre-</i> ‘hill’, with the transferred sense ‘eminence’, i.e. ‘exalted one’. See also   Bryan  . In Ireland there has also been some confusion with   O'Byrne   (see   Byrne  ).","History: This name is borne in particular by one of the greatest of Irish septs, descendants of Brian Boru, who rose to the high kingship of Ireland in 1002."],"variants":[{"name":"O'Brion","meanings":["Irish: variant of   O'Brien  ."]},{"name":"O'Bryon","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish William Kevin.","Irish: variant of   O'Brien  ."]},{"name":"Bryan","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Bryant  .","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of <b>Ó Briain</b>, see   O'Brien  ."]},{"name":"O'Briant","meanings":["Irish: variant of   O'Brien  , with excrescent <i>-t</i>."]},{"name":"O'Bryant","meanings":["Irish: variant of   O'Brien  ."]},{"name":"McBrien","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Seamus.","Irish:","Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Briain</b> ‘son of Brian’. See   O'Brien   and   Bryan  ."]},{"name":"O'Brian","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Liam.","Irish: variant of   O'Brien  ."]},{"name":"O'Bryan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish James Patrick, Padraic.","Irish: variant of   O'Brien  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1355924,"age":62,"year":"1547","julianDay":2286090,"description":"Henry VIII dies, succeeded by the boy king Edward VI. England and Ireland were ruled by the senior nobility of England.","jurisdiction